1. The "Clean Up" Challenge
Scenario: You’ve been working on a feature, but your commit history is a mess of "fixed typo" and "test" messages. You need to present a clean history to your team.

Task: Create a new branch, make 4 dummy commits with random messages.

The Goal: Use git rebase -i (interactive rebase) to squash those 4 commits into a single, well-named commit.

Bonus: Delete a file in one commit, then use git checkout to bring it back without reverting the whole commit.

2. The Merge Conflict Resolution
Scenario: You and a "colleague" (you, on a different branch) edited the same line of the same file.

Task: 1. Create a file app.txt on main with the text "Version 1.0".
2. Create branch feature-a, change the text to "Version A", and commit.
3. Switch back to main, change the text to "Version B", and commit.
4. Merge feature-a into main.

The Goal: Manually resolve the conflict in your editor, add the file, and complete the merge.

3. The "Oops, Wrong Branch" (Stash)
Scenario: You’ve spent 20 minutes coding a great feature, only to realize you’re still on the main branch and haven't committed yet. You aren't allowed to commit directly to main.

Task: 1. Make changes to a file on main.
2. Use git stash to "hide" those changes.
3. Create and switch to a new branch feature-fix.
4. Use git stash pop to bring your changes onto the correct branch.

The Goal: Successfully move uncommitted work from one branch to another without losing data.
